<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,903]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,313,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Remarks.</emphasis>
One of the specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[634,810,757,782]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="geographus">
<emphasis box="[634,810,757,782]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">C. geographus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected from Pamban resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Petuch" authorityYear="1979" box="[1239,1428,757,782]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fragilissimus">
<emphasis box="[1239,1428,757,782]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">C. fragilissimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, comparatively thinner and with sharp outer lip compared to other specimens (Figure 62M). The restricted distribution of this species to the 
<collectingRegion box="[506,559,837,863]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Gulf" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Gulf</collectingRegion>
of Mannar could be due to its preference for corals and sand bottoms with appropriate prey organisms.
</paragraph>
